      commentary: "Twelve verses, and this is the thesis: one syllable contains everything. Before dismissing that as mysticism, notice the word doing double duty. Akṣara means \"syllable\" — and it also means \"the imperishable.\" The pun is the teaching. The Mandukya is about to argue that if you examine any experience you have ever had or will ever have, it decomposes into a small number of states — and that the sound Om, decomposed into its own parts, maps onto them exactly. The syllable is not a magic noise. It is a compressed model of consciousness, small enough to hold in one breath.\n\nMark the scope of the claim, because the text is careful with it. Past, present, future — all Om. Then the strange extra clause: and whatever is beyond the three times, that too. The verse anticipates the obvious objection — \"surely reality is more than what shows up in time\" — and folds it in. Whatever can appear, and whatever the appearing happens within: one syllable claims both. This is the shortest Upanishad making the largest possible opening move, which is why the tradition treasured it so: Mandukya alone, it was said, is enough for the seeker of liberation.\n\nWhat does a modern reader do with this? Treat it as the table of contents it is. Verse two will say: this Self is Brahman, and it has four quarters. Verses three through seven walk the quarters — waking, dreaming, dreamless sleep, and turiya, \"the fourth,\" the awareness in which the other three come and go. Verses eight through twelve then map A, U, M onto the first three, and the silence after the sound onto the fourth. Everything you call your life happens in those states; you have never had an experience outside them. The Mandukya's wager is that if you understand the states and what witnesses them, you understand — not everything there is to know, but everything the knower is. The next eleven verses keep that promise with an economy no text has matched since."
